Propositional logic (also called sentential logic or Boolean logic) is the branch of logic that studies how whole statements combine and relate to each other using logical operators.

Think of it as the grammar of truth. It doesn’t care what the statement is about — only whether the statement is true or false and how it connects to other statements.

⸻

1. The Basic Idea

A proposition is a statement that can be either true (T) or false (F).

Examples:
	•	“The sky is blue.”
	•	“2 + 2 = 4.”
	•	“It is raining.”

Each of these can be treated like a variable:
	•	P = “It is raining.”
	•	Q = “The ground is wet.”

Propositional logic studies how P and Q interact.

⸻

2. The Core Logical Operators

These are the main “connectors” between propositions.

Operator	Symbol	Meaning	Example
NOT	¬	Negation	¬P = “Not P”
AND	∧	Both must be true	P ∧ Q
OR	∨	At least one true	P ∨ Q
IF–THEN	→	Implication	P → Q
IF AND ONLY IF	↔	Equivalence	P ↔ Q

Example:
	•	P = “It is raining”
	•	Q = “The ground is wet”

Statement:

P → Q

means

If it is raining, then the ground is wet.

⸻

3. Truth Tables

Propositional logic evaluates statements using truth tables.

Example for AND (∧)

P	Q	P ∧ Q
T	T	T
T	F	F
F	T	F
F	F	F

This simply means:

Both must be true for the statement to be true.

⸻

4. Why It Matters

Propositional logic is the foundation of:
	•	Computer programming
	•	Digital circuits
	•	AI reasoning
	•	Mathematical proofs
	•	Formal philosophy

Every computer chip literally runs on this logic:
	•	AND gates
	•	OR gates
	•	NOT gates

Your CPU is basically hardware propositional logic running billions of times per second.

⸻

5. What Propositional Logic Cannot Do

It only works on whole statements, not internal structure.

Example:

Propositional logic sees this as just P:

“All dogs are mammals.”

It doesn’t analyze the relationship between dogs and mammals.

To do that you need the next level:

Predicate Logic (First-Order Logic)

which can express things like:

\forall x (Dog(x) → Mammal(x))

meaning

For every x, if x is a dog, then x is a mammal.

⸻

6. Intuition

You can think of propositional logic as:

Algebra for truth.

Instead of numbers:

2 + 3

you manipulate truth values:

(P ∧ Q) → R

